way
to
it
and
this
must
be
the
case
with
Mr.
Elton;
a
most
valuable,
amiable,
pleasing
young
man
undoubtedly,
and
very
much
in
love
with
Harriet;
but
still,
he
cannot
refuse
an
invitation,
he
must
dine
out
wherever
he
is
asked.
What
a
strange
thing
love
is!
he
can
see
ready
wit
in
Harriet,
but
will
not
dine
alone
for
her."
Soon
afterwards
Mr.
Elton
quitted
them,
and
she
could
not
but
do
him
the
justice
of
feeling
that
there
was
a
great
deal
of
sentiment
in
his
manner
of
naming
Harriet
at
